{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568396"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20479"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20479"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.04,0.04,0.56,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101173"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13352"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83610"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"12404"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33413"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35121"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101173"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of itchy skin lesions that developed during his recent business trip to Paris. He stayed at a hotel for five nights and noticed the rash on the morning of his fourth day. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has not made any changes to his personal care products or diet during the trip. He practiced yoga on the carpet each morning and night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple erythematous papules on his arms, back, neck, and lower legs (image). Some lesions show evidence of excoriation. No vesicles, bullae, or pustules are present. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely finding if the patient\u0027s hotel room was to be inspected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carpet fibres containing pesticide residue","Formaldehyde residue from newly installed furniture","Airborne allergen particles from ventilation system","Rust-coloured spots on bed sheets and mattress seams","Mould growth on bathroom surfaces"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a case of bed bug bites acquired during travel. The clinical presentation of multiple erythematous, pruritic papules with a subtle linear pattern on exposed areas is characteristic. Bed bugs (\u003Cem\u003ECimex lectularius\u003C/em\u003E) are small, nocturnal insects that feed on human blood and can be found in various accommodations regardless of cleanliness or quality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERust-coloured spots on bed sheets and mattress seams\u003C/strong\u003E are a hallmark sign of bed bug infestation. These spots are actually bed bug excrement (digested blood) and are often found along with shed exoskeletons, eggs, and live bugs in the seams of mattresses, box springs, bed frames, and nearby furniture. Finding these spots would confirm the diagnosis of bed bug infestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMould growth on bathroom surfaces\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the patient\u0027s presentation. While mould exposure can cause respiratory symptoms and occasionally skin reactions, it typically does not cause the discrete papules seen in this patient. Additionally, mould reactions usually require prolonged exposure rather than developing after just a few days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarpet fibres containing pesticide residue\u003C/strong\u003E might cause a contact dermatitis, but this would typically present as a more diffuse rash in areas of direct contact with the carpet (which would occur during yoga practice). The pattern of discrete papules is not consistent with a contact dermatitis from pesticides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAirborne allergen particles from ventilation system\u003C/strong\u003E would more likely cause respiratory symptoms or a more generalised urticarial reaction rather than discrete papules. Additionally, such reactions would typically affect areas of skin that are both covered and uncovered by clothing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormaldehyde residue from newly installed furniture\u003C/strong\u003E could cause a contact dermatitis, but this would present differently from the patient\u0027s current rash. Contact dermatitis typically affects areas in direct contact with the allergen and presents as more confluent erythema, often with vesiculation, rather than discrete papules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of bed bug bites includes symptomatic treatment with antihistamines and topical corticosteroids for pruritus. Secondary bacterial infection from scratching may require antibiotics. Prevention of further bites involves thorough inspection of luggage before bringing it into one\u0027s home, washing all clothing in hot water, and careful inspection of hotel rooms (particularly the bed area) when travelling.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bed bug bites typically present as pruritic, erythematous papules in a linear or clustered pattern on exposed skin areas.","Diagnosis of bed bug infestation is based on clinical presentation, travel history, and identification of the insects or their traces.","Treatment of bed bug bites is symptomatic, focusing on antihistamines and topical corticosteroids for pruritus."],"references":["Doggett S, Russell R. Bed bugs [Internet]. Australian Family Physician. 2009: 38 (11). Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2009/november/bed-bugs","Image of \u0027bed bugs bites\u0027 by James Heilman MD (own work 2013) under CC BY-SA 3.0: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/. Image available at: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bed_bug#/media/File:Bedbugb2.JPG."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83610"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20479"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21841"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21841"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kvSkazKM2pEjmwEkQtNQRR2WS7PHzP.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kvSkazKM2pEjmwEkQtNQRR2WS7PHzP.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1154,"height":1200}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83610"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-30T19:49:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-30T19:50:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13352"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101173"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}}